    <name>
				<text>19.2.5.4 Solving an Exact Equation Ex1</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Solve the equation \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}({@f1@}) = {@f2@}\).</p>
<p>\(y =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] \( + \dfrac{C}{{@aa@}x^2}\), for some arbitrary constant \(C\). [[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p>We are given the equation \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}({@f1@}) = {@f2@}\) which is already in exact form.</p>
<p>Then, integrating both sides of the equation and rearranging, we obtain 
  \[\begin{aligned} {@aa@}yx^2 &amp;= \int {@bb@}x^{{@nn@}}\ \mathrm{d}x, \\
  \implies {@aa@}yx^2 &amp;= \frac{{@bb@}}{{@(nn+1)@}}x^{{@nn+1@}} + C, \\
  \implies y &amp;= {@bb/(aa*(nn+1))@}x^{{@nn-1@}} + \frac{C}{{@aa@}x^2}. \end{aligned}\]</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
